<?xml version="1.0" encoding="windows-1252"?>
<GeochemXYDiagram name="Alteration box plot">
   <GeochemFunctionAxisX name="AI" function="100*(m+k)/(m+n+c+k)" log="false"/>
   <GeochemFunctionAxisY name="CCPI" function="100*(m+(f+fe*0.8998122))/(m+n+(f+fe*0.8998122)+k)" log="false"/>
   <Comment>Chlorite Carbonate Pyrite Index vs Alteration Index. Fe must be reported as ferrous/ferric oxides and aliased to FeO* and Fe2O3*</Comment>
   <Comment>CCPI = 100*(MgO+(FeO+Fe2O3*0.8998122))/(MgO+Na2O+(FeO+Fe2O3*0.8998122)+K2O), AI = 100*(MgO+K2O)/MgO+Na2O+CaO+K2O)</Comment>
   <Comment>This diagram can be used to describe hydrothermal alteration of volcanic rocks, especially in a VMS deposit setting.</Comment>
   <Comment>Mineral names ab albite, adl adularia, il illite, chl chlorite, py pyrite, ep epidote, ca calcite, dol dolomite, ank ankerite</Comment>
   <Reference>Large, R.R. et al., 2001, The alteration box plot: A simple approach to understanding the relationships between alteration mineralogy and lithogeochemistry associated with VHMS deposits</Reference>
   <Reference>Economic Geology, vol. 96, pp. 957-971.</Reference>
   <Variable letter="F" element="FeO*" unit="pct"/>
   <Variable letter="FE" element="Fe2O3*" unit="pct"/>
   <Variable letter="K" element="K2O" unit="pct"/>
   <Variable letter="C" element="CaO" unit="pct"/>
   <Variable letter="N" element="Na2O" unit="pct"/>
   <Variable letter="M" element="MgO" unit="pct"/>
